# Website Route-Reactive Component Memoization

Applies when authoring or editing website components/layouts that read the current route at render time (`myInstance.getRouter().currentPage.identify`, `getRouter().isRTL`, `getRouter().locale`, or any `currentPage`/route-derived value used to shape rendered output).

## Rule

A component that derives rendered output from the current route MUST NOT be wrapped in `withMemo` (`React.memo`) with **no props**.

`withMemo` (`website/src/app/ui/base/components/Utils.tsx`) is `React.memo` with a shallow comparator that strips `extra`/`motion`/`hideAt`/`showAt`/`rotateAt` then `shallowEqual`s the rest. For a no-props component the remaining props are `{}` → `shallowEqual({}, {})` is true → the comparator returns "skip re-render" on every parent re-render. The component then renders exactly once (on mount) and is never re-rendered by its parent again — so any route-derived UI freezes on the first route seen after mount and goes stale on every subsequent navigation.

## How to comply

When a component depends on the current route, do one of:

1. **Export it without `withMemo`** — it re-renders whenever its layout parent re-renders (which happens on route change because the layout's `children` prop changes). This is the correct choice for header/breadcrumb-style components that are cheap to re-render.
2. **Pass the route-derived value as an explicit prop** (e.g. `identify`) so `withMemo`'s comparator sees it change and re-renders only when it actually changes.

## Canonical case

`LandingSubHeader` (and the customer-side `CustomerSubHeader`) build their breadcrumb via `useBreadcrumbs`, which reads `myInstance.getRouter().currentPage.identify` to walk the route's `breadcrumb` metadata (`Home -> Section -> Item`). Both are exported without `withMemo`. Wrapping either in `withMemo` with no props would freeze the breadcrumb: navigating between subpages re-renders the layout (its `children` changed) but would skip the sub-header, leaving the trail stuck on the first subpage.

Customer-shell canonical cases: `CustomerDrawer` (reads `getRouter().isRTL` for the drawer open side) and `CustomerBottomBar` (reads `currentPage.identify` for active nav state + `isRTL` for nav alignment) are exported **without** `withMemo`. `CustomerSubHeader` (reads `currentPage.identify` via `useBreadcrumbs`) is exported **without** `withMemo`. `Breadcrumb` receives `crumbs` as props and **may** use `withMemo`. `CustomerMainLayout` keeps `withMemo` and derives sub-header from `routes[identify]?.breadcrumb`, with `useCurrentPage()` for route-reactive identify. `CustomerHeader` and `CustomerFooter` keep `withMemo`. See `docs/platforms/website/flow-customer-shell.md` §11.

## What is NOT route-reactive (withMemo is fine)

Static components that do not read the route at render time (e.g. `LandingFooter`, `LandingHeader` with only anchor-scroll nav, presentational cards) may keep `withMemo` — their output does not change with the route, so skipping re-renders is a safe optimization.

## Why this is not obvious

`useMyInstance` / `useNav` / `useTranslator` return stable refs and do NOT subscribe to route changes — they do not trigger a re-render on navigation. Route-reactive components therefore rely entirely on parent-driven re-renders, which `withMemo`-no-props silently blocks.

